iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and I=E2=80=99ve =
been deep down the deep dive hole and we kinda just forgot to sell ads. Whi=
ch means that we have a practically clean slate.=20
I=E2=80=99m working with Nancy Xu [ https://substack.com/redirect/2e0edfd9-=
b0c3-488e-baec-84ba104b45d7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], who produced Age of Miracles, to build out the busin=
ess side of Not Boring. We=E2=80=99re looking for a handful of sponsors we =
can work closely with over the next couple of quarters, and hopefully much =
longer.=20
If you want to talk to the smartest, most curious group of people on the in=
ternet, the kind of people who are down to read 15,000 words on mining one =
week and fusion the next, let us know by clicking the button:
(1) Startup Brings New Hope to the Pursuit of Reviving Frozen Bodies [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/b88d8b34-c45a-463a-9f29-a295d4663135?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Ashlee Vance for Bloomberg Businessweek
On Monday, Deming plans [ https://substack.com/redirect/f88e50a1-9aac-4c9c-=
a544-35a33a457a22?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] to unveil Cradle Healthcare Co., which she=E2=80=99s been runni=
ng in secret for the past three years. The company=E2=80=99s focus is on tr=
ying to develop technology around reversible cryonics, placing people with =
illnesses into a frozen state and then reviving them at some stage in the f=
uture when cures for their ailments have arrived.
I said brr, it=E2=80=99s cold in here, there must be some ambitious founder=
 in the atmosphere.
Earlier this week, Laura Deming unveiled the cryonics company that she=E2=
=80=99s been working on in stealth for the last three years. Cryonics, whic=
h where popularized by the 1997 comedy blockbuster Austin Powers, is the pr=
actice of preserving legally dead individuals at extremely low temperatures=
 in hopes that future medical advancements will allow for their revival and=
 treatment. Deming=E2=80=99s company, Cradle Healthcare [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/2ed55cf5-dc0f-4dc6-a960-eb28536ad1f8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is pioneering reversible cryon=
ics by developing innovative cooling and rewarming technology that preserve=
s and revives biological function, focusing on minimizing ice crystal forma=
tion and optimizing cryoprotectant use.
The mission is super ambitious; the company=E2=80=99s website reads: =E2=80=
=9CPressing pause on biological time.=E2=80=9D Luckily, Deming is a force. =
In Ashlee Vance=E2=80=99s words:=20
She was a child prodigy in biotech who secured a laboratory research job at=
 the University of California, San Francisco, when she was 12 years old. At=
 14, she was accepted into the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and th=
en dropped out after two years to take one of the first entrepreneurial fel=
lowships offered by the billionaire Peter Thiel [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/6c0a0007-5b95-42a2-b739-ad8b5b90b221?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. At 19, she created the Longevity Fund =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/c523450c-e8fb-4241-b358-623ef05e3ddf?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which inves=
ted in more than a dozen companies. Today, in addition to running Cradle, D=
eming is co-founder and partner at Age1, a new longevity-focused investment=
 firm.
And now she has $48 million to pause biological time. Big win for the rest =
of us.=20
Cradle has shown  early promise, successfully experimenting with cooling an=
d rewarming rodent brain slices that retain neuronal activity, but is still=
 in the early stages of research and commercialization is at least a few ye=
ars out.=20
The company perfectly fits within my idea that our primary job as humans fo=
r the next ~5-10 years is to simply not die. I think if you can make it to =
2030 in reasonably good health, you=E2=80=99ll start adding years and years=
 of incremental lifespan. Medicine is getting so good, so fast. And if you =
contract some horribly complicated disease then maybe, through Cradle=E2=80=
=99s technology, you can just freeze yourself for a few years until the AI =
quantum computers spit out the new cure to your disease.=20
(2) STARSHIP LAUNCH [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc568e69-f7bc-4460-a1e0=
-ed9f12c46d82?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
Between Cradle and SpaceX, we might be able to live out the plot of every s=
pace sci-fi ever written: get frozen, travel a very, very long distance, an=
d wake up on the other side of the galaxy as if no time had passed.=20
SpaceX successfully launched Starship for the fourth time on Thursday. Watc=
hing Starship, the largest and most powerful rocket ever created, launch is=
 a real thing of beauty=E2=80=A6so if you haven=E2=80=99t watched yet, stop=
 reading and go watch the video.
The goal of this launch was to prove out some reusability characteristics o=
f the craft, and by all accounts, SpaceX achieved the goal. Starship execut=
ed a landing burn and had a soft splashdown in the Gulf of Mexico, as plann=
ed.
Even The New York Time=E2=80=99s had to admit, SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starship Ro=
cket Successfully Completes 1st Return From Space [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/f5bf259c-a467-4ee7-bd8d-c5f76def6eed?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
What was maybe most remarkable about this launch is how under control it al=
l felt. Until that heroic flap started melting off, everything kind of just=
 worked as planned. By the time our kids are our age, Starship launches mig=
ht feel just as routine as commercial airline flights do today. Until then,=
 though, I=E2=80=99m going to enjoy the plasma out of each and every one of=
 these launches.=20
(3) LIFTOFF! NASA Astronauts Pilot First Starliner Crewed Test to Station [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/8fb797a7-3bd9-4062-9351-50ceb6b1b316?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From NASA
=E2=80=9CTwo bold NASA astronauts are well on their way on this historic fi=
rst test flight of a brand-new spacecraft,=E2=80=9D said NASA Administrator=
 Bill Nelson. =E2=80=9CBoeing=E2=80=99s Starliner marks a new chapter of Am=
erican exploration. Human spaceflight is a daring task =E2=80=93 but that=
=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s worth doing. It=E2=80=99s an exciting time for =
NASA, our commercial partners, and the future of exploration. Go Starliner,=
 Go Butch and Suni!=E2=80=9D
SpaceX, for once, wasn=E2=80=99t the only company that successfully launche=
d a reusable rocket this week.=20
Boeing needed a win and earlier this week, they got one.
On Wednesday, after delays and $1.4 billion in cost overruns, Boeing succes=
sfully launched and sent NASA astronauts Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams on=
 the Starliner=E2=80=99s first crewed flight test to the International Spac=
e Station (ISS), an important step for NASA as it gets back in the crewed-f=
light business. The goal of the mission was to validate the Starliner syste=
m, ensuring it=E2=80=99s ready for regular astronaut transport to and fro t=
he ISS. Mission accomplished.
Yesterday, Starliner successfully docked at the ISS, where Wilmore and Will=
iams joined the international crew.=20
The launch was particularly important for Boeing, which proved it could del=
iver a fully operational reusable spacecraft. The company, whose reputation=
 has been damaged from it=E2=80=99s troubles in commercial aviation and the=
 short shelf life of its whistleblowers, finally did a good.=20
Honestly, we were pretty worried for the astronauts. Great to see them smil=
ing from space. And the more companies building and selling reusable rocket=
s that don=E2=80=99t blow up, the better, IMO.=20
(4) $35 Billion Georgia nuclear reactors are celebrated, but Biden Administ=
ration wants 98 more [ https://substack.com/redirect/eee41bca-aa06-4c88-aa8=
7-4e36ee7fc82a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]
From the Associated Press
U.S. Energy Secretary Jennifer Granholm stated, "We have to at least triple=
 our current nuclear capacity in this country to reach our goal of getting =
to net zero by 2050" while celebrating the nearly $35 billion investment in=
 new reactors at Georgia's Plant Vogtle=E2=80=8B.
What is this a nuclear network for ants? This needs to be at least=E2=80=A6=
three times bigger.
While U.S. Energy Secretary Jennifer Granholm celebrated the recent opening=
 of tower three at Georgia=E2=80=99s Plant Vogle, she also made it very cle=
ar that the U.S. has a ton of work ahead. There are currently 93 commercial=
ly operating nuclear reactors in the U.S. spread out across 54 sites and 28=
 states, and nuclear currently accounts for just under 20% of electricity g=
eneration. According to Granholm, nuclear capacity needs to expand by 3x in=
 order for the country to hit its emissions goals.
Even those who don=E2=80=99t care about climate change want more nuclear. P=
er the article, =E2=80=9CGeorgia Gov. Brian Kemp floated the idea of a fift=
h Vogtle reactor. Although the Republican Kemp rarely discusses climate cha=
nge, he has made electric vehicles a priority and has said new industries d=
emand carbon-free electricity.=E2=80=9D
And if there=E2=80=99s a bipartisan will, there=E2=80=99s certainly a way. =
Despite projects being long delayed and way over budget, there seems to be =
the political desire to support and prioritize nuclear buildout.=20
On Wednesday, the Biden Administration said that it would create a working =
group to make it easier to build nuclear, and proposed some ideas that we c=
an get behind (and discussed on Age of Miracles [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/198901f4-8122-4904-8daf-360809547d3a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]):=20
Military reactor purchases to help bring nuclear down the cost curve.=20
Replacing closing coal plants with small reactors.=20
Further streamline licensing (we=E2=80=99d prefer to see the NRC shut down,=
 but hey)=20
Those measures, combined with growing nuclear popularity and a rising class=
 of nuclear startups, may be enough to overcome the boundaries that have pr=
evented previous nuclear buildouts in this country.
More energy is good. Let=E2=80=99s go build it.=20
(5) Harnessing the energy of the stars =E2=80=A6 in a bottle | Fuse [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/1854f786-c118-4034-83ea-840a0ae7c7f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Jason Carman for S3
Packy here. Last week, I wrote about one of my favorite companies: Fuse Ene=
rgy [ https://substack.com/redirect/c6b99815-b418-444d-bfa0-280b3876b50d?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Founder JC Btaiche and co. are building pulsed power generators that can be=
 used for radiation effects testing en route to commercial fusion power. It=
=E2=80=99s simultaneously wildly ambitious and surprisingly practical.
On Monday, my friend Jason Carman [ https://substack.com/redirect/302225c8-=
fd7c-442c-bc84-6db39547b967?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] dropped an excellent S3 video on Fuse (and an intervi=
ew with JC [ http://And it you want even more F ]), featuring interviews of=
 the team and a look at TITAN firing. It=E2=80=99s a banger, and I particul=
arly enjoyed hearing Dr. Vahid Damideh joyfully explain fusion, what they=
=E2=80=99re building at Fuse, and why:=20
What fusion scientists believe, they think if we achieve energy from fusion=
, since energy will be limitless, all energy wars all over the world will s=
top. This is the dream for all fusion scientists all over the world.
Until that day, Fuse is also working to help prevent nuclear war, a goal th=
at keeps getting more important for the US government. Semafor reported [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/4493bc8e-4a95-4721-8d5c-a850c17f0729?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that the Biden =
administration =E2=80=9Cwill announce its intention to embrace a more asser=
tive nuclear weapons strategy=E2=80=9D later today after China and Russia h=
ave spurned arms control conversations over the past year. Fuse may play a =
critically important role in modernizing the nuclear arsenal, to bring peac=
e through strength.=20
I, for one, hope they pull it off. There are too many amazing things I want=
 to live to see for us to bump into the Great Filter.
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

